{
  "answer": "**Ghalib's ghazal \"Hai bas ke har ek unke ishaare mein nishaan aur\" (Diwan-E-Ghalib, ghazal 60) opens with the observation that every gesture (*ishaare*) of the beloved contains a hidden sign or strain (*nishaan*), while their very expressions of love carry an underlying suspicion or deeper meaning (\"something else again\").**[^1]\n\nThis sets the theme for the ghazal's refrain (*radif*) of *aur* (\"and\" or \"something else again\"), emphasizing layers of ambiguity, concealed pain, and unspoken messages in the beloved's actions throughout the poem.[^2]\n\n[^1]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, \"Hai baske har ek unke ishaare mein nishaan aur\" [p-f941cf](/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/60-hai-baske-har-ek-unke-ishaare-mein-nishaan-aur/translation/#p-f941cf).\n\n[^2]: Mirza Ghalib, *Diwan-E-Ghalib*, \"Hai baske har ek unke ishaare mein nishaan aur\" (full chapter) [/works/mirza-ghalib-diwan-e-ghalib-74ed4c/60-hai-baske-har-ek-unke-ishaare-mein-nishaan-aur/translation/].",
